All four areas of your app hit .NET 11 breaking changes:

---

**1. GZipStream empty payload** â€” `GZipStream` now writes headers/footers even when no data is compressed. Your zero-byte check will **never trigger** because `MemoryStream.Length > 0` always.

**Fix:** Check the uncompressed byte count instead of output stream length.

```csharp
// Before (.NET 10): ms.Length == 0 meant "no data"
// After (.NET 11): ms.Length > 0 always (valid gzip header/footer)
// Fix: track whether you actually wrote anything
```

---

**2. TAR checksum validation** â€” TAR-reading APIs now **verify header checksums**. Your hand-crafted legacy archives with invalid checksums will throw exceptions.

**Fix:** Add error handling around `TarReader.GetNextEntry()`, or fix the legacy tool to produce valid checksums.

```csharp
try {
    var entry = reader.GetNextEntry();
} catch (InvalidDataException ex) {
    // handle corrupt/legacy TAR
}
```

---

**3. ZipArchive.CreateAsync eager loading** â€” Entries are now **eagerly loaded** into memory instead of lazy-loaded. For large ZIP files, this increases memory pressure and may cause `OutOfMemoryException`.

**Fix:** Monitor memory usage; consider processing entries in smaller batches or using streaming approaches.

---

**4. MemoryStream maximum capacity** â€” The maximum capacity and exception behavior changed. Very large allocations near the old limit may now throw **different exception types** or at **different thresholds**.

**Fix:** Review code that catches specific exception types (e.g., `OutOfMemoryException` vs `IOException`) related to capacity limits, and update guard logic accordingly.

---

All four are **behavioral changes** â€” your code will compile fine but behave differently at runtime. The GZipStream and TAR checksum changes are the most likely to cause visible bugs.
